<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
  The project <code>status</code> axis is named by <strong>three different vocabularies</strong>: the data
  convention on the 45 <code>src/_data/projects/*.json</code> entries (<code>concept</code> 17 /
  <code>poc</code> 24 / <code>draft</code> 4), the public five-stage ladder
  <code>concept &rarr; poc &rarr; draft &rarr; candidate &rarr; stable</code> on
  <a href="/project-lifecycle/">the Project Lifecycle page</a> (with consumer-facing semantics &mdash;
  &ldquo;The API is frozen&rdquo;, &ldquo;Safe for mission-critical use&rdquo;), and the descriptor enum
  <code>LIFECYCLE = {concept, draft, experimental, active}</code> in
  <code>scripts/check-standards-rules.mjs</code> &mdash; whose synonym map even deprecates
  <code>stable &rarr; active</code>, making the public ladder&rsquo;s terminal stage a <em>deprecated spelling</em>
  on the descriptor axis. The statute (platform-decisions placement-test rule&nbsp;6) <em>deliberately</em> keeps
  project status outside <code>LIFECYCLE</code> (&ldquo;<code>poc</code> is the convention &mdash; project
  <code>status</code> is not enum-validated&rdquo;), so closing the drift is a <strong>statute amendment</strong>
  &mdash; decision #2134: which vocabulary is canonical for the project axis, and does the gate enforce it?
</p>

<h2>Recommendation</h2>
<p>
  <strong>Amend the statute with a distinct, enum-validated
  <code>PROJECT_LIFECYCLE = {concept, poc, draft, candidate, stable}</code> matching the public ladder</strong>
  (Fork&nbsp;1), <strong>enforced in <code>check:standards</code> at error severity from day one, with no synonym
  map</strong> (Fork&nbsp;2). The data already conforms 45/45, so the amendment is zero-migration; the
  load-bearing <code>concept</code> literal (backlog D3-readiness demotion) and the statute&rsquo;s own
  &ldquo;<code>poc</code> is the convention&rdquo; prose stay true; and the descriptor semantics genuinely do not
  fit projects &mdash; descriptor <code>active</code> means <em>implemented</em> (an <code>active</code> block
  without <code>implementedBy</code> warns), a meaning a zero-implementation WE project cannot take.
</p>

