<h2>Prior art &mdash; how mature ecosystems keep a status vocabulary honest</h2>
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>System</th><th>Label set</th><th>Normative home</th><th>Validated?</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>W3C Process</td><td>WD &rarr; CR &rarr; PR &rarr; REC (+ Note track)</td><td>the Process Document, one closed definition</td><td>process gates per transition</td></tr>
    <tr><td>TC39</td><td>Stages 0&ndash;4</td><td>process document</td><td>the proposals table is maintained against it</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Node.js</td><td>Stability 0 deprecated / 1 experimental / 2 stable / 3 legacy</td><td>docs metadata (machine-readable index)</td><td>yes &mdash; tooling reads the index</td></tr>
    <tr><td>USWDS / Polaris / Carbon</td><td>small closed component-lifecycle enums</td><td>design-system docs config</td><td>enforced by docs tooling</td></tr>
    <tr><td>npm dist-tags</td><td><em>free-form publisher labels</em> (<code>latest</code>, <code>next</code>, &hellip;)</td><td>none &mdash; declared ad hoc</td><td><strong>no &mdash; the drift counter-model</strong>; only <code>latest</code> is special-cased</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
<p>
  Two lessons transfer. <strong>(1) One closed normative home + mechanical validation:</strong> drift arises
  exactly where a label set lives in prose, data, and tooling separately &mdash; WE&rsquo;s current shape; npm
  dist-tags show the endpoint of the unvalidated path. <strong>(2) Distinct tracks keep distinct ladders:</strong>
  W3C does not reuse TC39&rsquo;s stages and Node&rsquo;s stability index is not npm&rsquo;s tags &mdash; because
  the processes being measured differ. WE descriptors mature toward <em>implementation</em>
  (<code>active</code> &rArr; <code>implementedBy</code>); WE projects mature toward <em>spec stability</em>
  (<code>candidate</code> = API frozen, <code>stable</code> = SemVer). Two ordered enums for two maturation
  processes is the surveyed shape, which is why the recommendation is a <em>distinct</em>
  <code>PROJECT_LIFECYCLE</code>, not a merge into the descriptor <code>LIFECYCLE</code>.
</p>

<h2>The forks (decision #2134)</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Fork 1 &mdash; canonical vocabulary:</strong> <strong>(a) distinct
    <code>PROJECT_LIFECYCLE</code> = the public ladder</strong> (zero migration; <code>concept</code> literal
    untouched; per-track ladders) vs (b) merge into descriptor <code>LIFECYCLE</code> (rejected: 24-file
    <code>poc &rarr; experimental</code> migration, public-page rewrite, and the imported
    <code>stable &rarr; active</code> synonym would forbid the catalog from ever saying the word its own ladder
    promises as terminal) vs (c) a fresh third label set (rejected broken: a fourth vocabulary). Word-reuse
    caution: <code>stable</code> becomes canonical-for-Project while staying a deprecated descriptor synonym
    &mdash; fine because the checks are kind-keyed, but the amendment must state the reuse explicitly.</li>
  <li><strong>Fork 2 &mdash; enforcement:</strong> <strong>(a) enum-validate in <code>check:standards</code>,
    error severity, day one, no synonym map</strong> (data already clean; the tier precedent is adjacent in the
    same file; status rules &ldquo;never warn&rdquo; by house design) vs (b) convention-only (rejected: the exact
    enforcement gap that produced three definitions plus a stray fourth spelling) vs (c) warn-only (rejected:
    contradicts the never-warn shape).</li>
</ul>

<h2>Not forks</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Statute amendment mechanics (rewriting rule 6&rsquo;s parenthetical, adding the anchor) &mdash;
    codification at ratification, never a prep-time edit.</li>
  <li>Check placement / function naming &mdash; implementation detail below the observable gate contract.</li>
  <li>Auto-deriving the ladder page from the enum &mdash; declared-over-auto-derived; the gate guaranteeing
    data &sube; enum is the drift that matters.</li>
  <li>Cleanup of the orphaned root specs (<code>webhandlers.json</code> with its stray
    <code>speculative</code>, the stale duplicate <code>webportals.json</code>) &mdash; a follow-up build filed
    on ratification.</li>
</ul>

